parameters.description: Log baseline natural mortality rate of juvenile COTS (non-predation mortality)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log baseline annual natural mortality rate of juvenile COTS (age 0-2 years) from disease, starvation, and other non-predation sources

parameters.description: Log baseline predation mortality rate on juvenile COTS under normal predator effectiveness
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log baseline annual predation mortality rate on juvenile COTS when predators are fully effective (not saturated). This represents mortality from fish predators (humphead wrasse, coral trout, emperor fish) and invertebrate predators (triton snails). Expected to be substantial (0.5-2.0 year^-1) as predation is the primary control on juvenile COTS under normal conditions.

parameters.description: Log juvenile COTS density at which predators become 50% saturated (half-maximal effectiveness)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log critical juvenile COTS density threshold at which predator effectiveness is reduced by half due to saturation of consumption capacity. This represents the density at which COTS begin to 'swamp' predator control, initiating outbreak conditions. Lower values indicate predators are more easily overwhelmed. Range 0.01-0.5 individuals/m2 reflects empirical observations of outbreak thresholds.

parameters.description: Steepness of predator saturation response curve (Hill coefficient)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Hill coefficient controlling the sharpness of transition in predator effectiveness as COTS density increases. Higher values create sharper thresholds for outbreak initiation, producing more episodic boom-bust dynamics. Range 2-6 captures gradual to very sharp transitions in predator control.

parameters.description: Strength of coral refuge effect on predation mortality (0=no effect, 1=complete protection)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Maximum fractional reduction in predation mortality when coral refuge is abundant. May be stronger than refuge effect on natural mortality because structural complexity specifically hides juveniles from visual predators. Range 0.5-0.9 reflects that predation is more strongly affected by habitat structure than disease/starvation.

parameters.description: Log rate at which juvenile COTS mature to reproductive adults
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log annual maturation rate from juvenile to adult stage (inverse of maturation time: 0.5/year = 2 year maturation period)

parameters.description: Relative feeding efficiency of juvenile COTS compared to adults
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Fraction of adult feeding rate achieved by juveniles (0.1-0.8 range reflects smaller size and lower consumption capacity)

parameters.description: Log Allee threshold density of adults below which recruitment is reduced
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log Allee threshold density for adult COTS reducing reproductive success

parameters.description: Strength of Allee effect on adult COTS reproduction (0=no effect, 1=maximum effect)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Strength of Allee effect on adult COTS reproduction (0–1 scale)

parameters.description: Log density-dependent mortality coefficient for adult COTS
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log density-dependent mortality coefficient for adult COTS (m2/ind/year)

parameters.description: Log coral cover providing 50% of maximum refuge benefit to juvenile COTS (half-saturation constant)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log half-saturation coral cover for refuge effect on juvenile COTS survival (% cover at which refuge benefit is half-maximal). Range 10-60% reflects typical reef coral cover providing meaningful structural complexity.

parameters.description: Maximum proportional reduction in juvenile COTS natural mortality due to coral refuge (0=no effect, 1=complete protection)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Maximum fractional reduction in juvenile natural (non-predation) mortality when coral refuge is abundant (0-1 scale). Range 0.3-0.8 reflects empirical observations that juvenile survival from disease/starvation increases 2-5x in high-complexity habitats.

parameters.description: Steepness of coral refuge response curve (Hill coefficient controlling transition sharpness)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Hill coefficient controlling sharpness of transition in refuge effect with coral cover (1=hyperbolic, >1=sigmoidal). Range 1-4 captures gradual to sharp transitions in habitat quality.
